13. postquam...inierat. The interposition, in the midst of oratio obliqua, of a subordinate clause in the indic. is not uncommon in Tacitus. Cf. quarn...strnoeerat (below). There are several instances with (lum (with present).

15. auctam suspicionem tamquam...inrogaret‚ a thoroughly Tacitean form of speech. Translate, ‘and thus enhanced his father's suspicion that he was inflicting on himself....’ Cf. c. 13.
